an entity that can either be directly located on a genome (gene, transcript, exon, regulatory region) or is encoded in a genome (protein)
An information content entity that describes a genome by specifying the total variation in genomic sequence and/or gene expression, relative to some extablished background
The label for the taxon class or ancestor class for the object
a closure slot that includes a taxon and all ancestral taxa
a concept or class in an ontology, vocabulary or thesaurus

connects an association to the subject of the association. For example, in a gene-to-phenotype association, the gene is subject and phenotype is object.
abstract parent class for different kinds of gene-gene or gene product to gene product relationships. Includes homology and interaction.
For example, a particular exon is part of a particular transcript or gene
A stage of development or growth of an organism, including post-natal adult stages

Any published piece of information. Can refer to a whole publication, or to a part of it (e.g. a figure, figure legend, or section highlighted by NLP). The scope is intended to be general and include information published on the web as well as journals.

any grouping of multiple genes or gene products

An interaction between a chemical entity or substance and a gene or gene product. The chemical substance may be a drug with the gene being a target of the drug.

a databased entity or concept/class
A genomic feature representing one of a set of coexisting sequence variants at a particular genomic locus.
The value in a property-value tuple
The label for the taxon class or ancestor class for the subject

Ancestors (reflexive) of the object field following is_a (subClassOf) and part-of links. This is typically used as a query constraint and for faceting. The combination of is_a and part of is a common pattern, and can be used in gene expression queries (finding genes that are expressed in a structure, a subtype, or a part of that structure) or in GO queries (in any of the three branches of GO)
a qualifier used in a phenotypic association to state when the phenotype appears is in the subject
connects an association to an supporting entity. May be a gene/product (if evidence is homology or protein interaction). Same as WITH/FROM column in GO/GAFs
Any association between an environment and a phenotypic feature, where being in the environment influences the phenotype
An association between a gene and an expression site, possibly qualified by stage/timing info. TBD: introduce subclasses for distinction between wild-type and experimental conditions?
any grouping of multiple genes or gene products related by common descent

Additional relationships that are true of the subject in the context of the association. For example, if the subject is a gene product in a functional association, the subject extensions may represent  an isoform or a specific post-translational state
A gene, gene product, small molecule or macromolecule (including protein complex)
A typed association between two entities, supported by evidence
the relationship type by which a subject is connected to an object in an association
a long-form human readable name for a thing

Ancestors (reflexive) of the object field following is_a (subClassOf), part-of and regulates (including positive and negative) relationships. This is typically used as a query constraint and for faceting where the range is a biological process
any slot that relates an association to another entity
may be a chemical entity or a formulation with a chemical entity as active ingredient, or a complex material with multiple chemical entities as part
An interaction between a chemical entity and a phenotype or disease, where the presence of the chemical gives rise to or exacerbates the phenotype
